@gostislavszaposki Yea. I saw it afterwards in other posts. It is also abt not understanding the condition. I shared this under one one outraged comment: 
- About 10  to 15% of ppl w/ tourettes also suffer from coprolalia or the involuntary shouting out inappropriate things. -- "The leading explanation ties into how the brain processes suppression and inhibition. The very act of thinking "I must not say that word right now" may actually activate and amplify that word in the brain — similar to the classic psychological effect where if someone tells you not to think of a pink elephant, you immediately do. For someone with compromised inhibitory control in the brain, this backfire effect may be much stronger. It is not malicious or subconscious desire. This is important — it doesn't reflect what the person wants to say, their true feelings, or repressed desires (a Freudian interpretation some people mistakenly apply). It's a neurological misfiring, not a revelation of hidden thoughts.


Precisely because the outbursts tend toward maximum inappropriateness, coprolalia is often deeply embarrassing and distressing for the people experiencing it — they are usually acutely aware of how it sounds to others. It's a cruel irony of the condition in some ways."  -Claude ai

